   <mods:abstract>This dissertation provides a comparison of religious ethics between Christian and Muslim sources to describe an anti-imperial liberation ethic. It takes three subjects – Gustavo Gutierrez, Camilo Torres, and Ali Shariati – and extrapolates from their writings a three-part framework to facilitate this comparison. This framework consists of: 1) a theory of oppression (from which one is liberated); 2) a critique of the status quo, both politically and theologically; and, 3) a focus on experience and praxis. The comparisons made and the framework provided will help to justify intuitive comparisons by other scholars as well as establish future comparisons of liberation theologies.</mods:abstract>
